From: cyy <cyyever@gmail.com>
Date: Wed, 23 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] macOS: msync msg_queue wake consistency (fix GUI message-wait
 lost wakeup)

msync_wake_up()/msync_clear() resolved the wake shm index via
get_obj_inproc_sync(), which returns -1 for the msg_queue's server-backed
event_sync on macOS (there is no inproc/ntsync shadow here). The queue's own
dedicated msync shm was therefore never signaled, so a client blocked in a GUI
message wait (MsgWaitForMultipleObjects) never woke -- the CEF steamwebhelper
watchdog then fired "Steamwebhelper is not responding".

Fall back to the object's own get_msync_idx for the msg_queue in both
msync_wake_up() and msync_clear() (gated to the queue so no other server-backed
object's dormant msync path is touched), and admit the queue to the client
msync fast-path in the get_msync_idx handler. is_msg_queue() is a small helper
added in server/queue.c (declared in server/msync.h) since msg_queue_ops is
file-local to queue.c.

Can be folded into 0008-macos-msync.patch later.

diff --git a/server/msync.c b/server/msync.c
--- a/server/msync.c
+++ b/server/msync.c
@@ -814,6 +814,18 @@
 
     if ((idx = get_obj_inproc_sync( obj, &type )) > 0)
         msync_signal_all( idx );
+    else if (is_msg_queue( obj ))
+    {
+        /* The msg_queue is the one object with a real server-side sync (so
+         * get_obj_inproc_sync() returns -1 above on macOS, no inproc shadow) that
+         * ALSO owns a dedicated msync shm via get_msync_idx and is handed to msync
+         * clients (see the get_msync_idx handler). Signal that shm -- exactly the
+         * index a GUI message wait blocks on -- or it never wakes. Gated to the
+         * queue so no other server-backed object's dormant msync path is touched. */
+        enum msync_type mtype;
+        unsigned int midx = obj->ops->get_msync_idx( obj, &mtype );
+        if (midx) msync_signal_all( midx );
+    }
 }
 
 void msync_destroy_semaphore( unsigned int shm_idx )
@@ -846,6 +858,15 @@
 
     if ((idx = get_obj_inproc_sync( obj, &type )) > 0)
         msync_clear_shm( idx );
+    else if (is_msg_queue( obj ))
+    {
+        /* Symmetric with msync_wake_up(): clear the queue's own msync shm so a
+         * level-triggered client wait sees it go unsignaled instead of spinning on
+         * a stale signaled flag. Gated to the queue, as above. */
+        enum msync_type mtype;
+        unsigned int midx = obj->ops->get_msync_idx( obj, &mtype );
+        if (midx) msync_clear_shm( midx );
+    }
 }
 
 void msync_set_event( struct msync *msync )
@@ -961,20 +982,26 @@
     if (!(obj = get_handle_obj( current->process, req->handle, SYNCHRONIZE, NULL )))
         return;
 
-    /* Hand the client an msync shm index ONLY for objects that cannot be waited
+    /* Hand the client an msync shm index for objects that cannot be waited
      * server-side -- i.e. pure msync primitives (events/mutexes/sems created via
-     * create_msync), whose sync is the object itself with add_queue == no_add_queue.
+     * create_msync), whose sync is the object itself with add_queue == no_add_queue
+     * -- PLUS the msg_queue, which maintains its own dedicated msync shm through the
+     * dual signal path in queue.c (signal_sync/reset_sync for server waiters AND
+     * msync_wake_up/msync_clear for msync waiters). The queue was excluded before
+     * because msync_wake_up() resolved the wake index via get_obj_inproc_sync(),
+     * which returns -1 for the queue's server-backed sync on macOS -> its wakeups
+     * were dropped and a GUI message wait hung; msync_wake_up()/msync_clear() now
+     * fall back to the object's own get_msync_idx, so msync-waiting the queue is
+     * correct and lets a MsgWait be a pure msync wait instead of a polling
+     * msync+server mixed wait.
      *
-     * Objects that DO have a real server-side sync (process/thread/msg_queue ->
-     * event_sync, add_queue works) must keep SERVER waits: their server-side
-     * wakeups are reliable, whereas routing them to client msync exposed a
-     * lost-wakeup hang (Steam's GUI message loop blocked forever on its queue +
-     * driver events). Conversely, the inproc_sync path used here before is the
-     * ntsync (Linux) mechanism, stubbed on macOS -- it reported "no shadow" for
-     * every real msync primitive, so those got server-selected and spun on
-     * no_add_queue -> STATUS_OBJECT_TYPE_MISMATCH (Steam's "stalled pipe"). */
+     * process/thread stay on SERVER waits (their sync is a server event_sync with a
+     * real add_queue and they have no dual msync path). The inproc_sync path used
+     * here is the ntsync (Linux) mechanism, stubbed on macOS -- returning the object
+     * itself from default_get_sync() keeps real msync primitives off no_add_queue ->
+     * STATUS_OBJECT_TYPE_MISMATCH (Steam's "stalled pipe"). */
     sync = get_obj_sync( obj );
-    if (obj->ops->get_msync_idx && sync->ops->add_queue == no_add_queue)
+    if (obj->ops->get_msync_idx && (sync->ops->add_queue == no_add_queue || is_msg_queue( obj )))
         idx = obj->ops->get_msync_idx( obj, &type );
     release_object( sync );
 
diff --git a/server/queue.c b/server/queue.c
--- a/server/queue.c
+++ b/server/queue.c
@@ -199,6 +199,14 @@
     no_close_handle,           /* close_handle */
     msg_queue_destroy          /* destroy */
 };
+
+/* True for a thread message queue. Used by the msync get_msync_idx handler to
+ * admit the queue to the client msync fast-path (it owns a dedicated msync shm
+ * kept in sync via msync_wake_up/msync_clear), unlike other server-backed syncs. */
+int is_msg_queue( struct object *obj )
+{
+    return obj->ops == &msg_queue_ops;
+}
 
 static const struct fd_ops msg_queue_fd_ops =
 {
diff --git a/server/msync.h b/server/msync.h
--- a/server/msync.h
+++ b/server/msync.h
@@ -27,6 +27,7 @@
 extern void msync_destroy_semaphore( unsigned int shm_idx );
 extern void msync_wake_up( struct object *obj );
 extern void msync_clear( struct object *obj );
+extern int is_msg_queue( struct object *obj );
 
 struct msync;
 
